            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Leo Mendoza Chan is a product of the very intersections he now serves. Born and raised in the Mission District, his childhood was a vibrant mix of his mother's Filipino warmth\u2014the aroma of adobo filling their small apartment\u2014and his father's steadfast Chinese-American pragmatism. His lola, his maternal grandmother, was the heart of the home, a woman who spoke in a gentle mix of Tagalog and broken English. Watching her struggle to navigate the cold maze of city bureaucracy and healthcare systems planted a seed in young Leo\u2019s mind. He saw how easily people could fall through the cracks, especially those caught between cultures and languages.\n\nHis path wasn't always clear. He initially enrolled at SF State with a vague business major, influenced by his father\u2019s practical advice. The turning point came during his junior year when his lola passed away after a prolonged illness, a period marked by frustrating battles with insurance and social services. The experience was a painful crystallization of his purpose. He switched his major to social welfare, driven by a newfound fire. He went on to earn his Master of Social Work from the same university, focusing his thesis on program development for multigenerational immigrant households.\n\nNow, at 35, Leo is the Program Director at the Mission Neighborhood Hub, a community center a mere 0.8 miles from the apartment he now rents. His life is woven into the fabric of his community. His commute is a short walk past the murals and taquerias of his youth. His days are a whirlwind of grant writing, managing after-school programs, and counseling seniors. He knows the names of the kids who play basketball in the center\u2019s gym and the shop owners he passes daily. His social life consists of a tight-knit circle of friends, mostly fellow social workers, who meet for cheap beers and vent about their demanding but rewarding jobs.\n\nLeo\u2019s dream is to secure a permanent future for the center. He fears displacement more than anything, watching as gentrification pushes out the very families the hub was created to support. His greatest aspiration is to lead a capital campaign to buy their building, creating a permanent bulwark against the changing tides of the city and ensuring that for generations to come, there will always be a place of welcome, just like the home his lola once made."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the cold vinyl chair at the social services office, his small hand lost in his lola\u2019s. He was ten. He watched her try to explain, her gentle Tagalog rhythm faltering against the clipped, impatient English of the woman behind the glass. He felt a hot, helpless anger rise in his chest. His lola, the unshakable heart of their home, was made to feel small and lost. In that sterile room, he felt the first stirrings of a fierce, protective duty: to become the voice she never had.\n\n2.\nHe was a junior in college, on hold with an insurance agent about his lola\u2019s care. The agent used the word \u201cineligible.\u201d The single word, so clinical and final, cut through his grief and ignited a cold fury. He looked at his business textbook, its neat columns and profit margins suddenly obscene. He slammed the phone down, his hands shaking. That callous word wasn't just a rejection; it was a call to arms. The next day, he walked into the registrar\u2019s office and changed his major to social welfare.\n\n3.\nJust after getting his MSW, he helped a new Filipina grandmother navigate the Medi-Cal application. She reminded him so much of his lola, clutching her papers with the same worried expression. When he spoke a few words of Tagalog to her, her face softened from fear into a deep, trusting relief. In her grateful smile, Leo felt a profound click of purpose. He hadn't been able to do this for his lola, but he could do it for her, and for all the lolas to come.\n\n4.\nLast year, Rodriguez Panaderia closed. Leo had bought pan de sal there since he was a kid. He saw Mr. Rodriguez packing the last of his things, the empty shelves echoing with sixty years of history. The man just shook his head, his eyes tired. \"The rent, Leo. The rent.\" Seeing that \"For Lease\" sign felt like a physical blow. It wasn't just a bakery; it was an anchor. Its disappearance made his fight to buy the Hub\u2019s building feel less like an aspiration and more like a desperate race against time.\n\n5.\nA few weeks ago, he stood in the doorway of the Hub's main hall. In the gym, teenagers were playing basketball. To his left, a group of seniors were laughing over coffee and mahjong. He saw a fifth-grader he\u2019d been counseling high-five one of the old-timers. The mix of sounds\u2014the bouncing ball, the clacking tiles, the Spanglish chatter\u2014was the most beautiful music. It was chaotic, vibrant, and alive. This, he thought, his chest tight with emotion, is the home worth fighting for. This is my lola's legacy."
